21:12.725 --> 21:20.054
From 1983 on, we were buying large collections and single items.

21:20.074 --> 21:26.362
Initially, we bought large collections just to have a collection in order to fill in.

21:26.382 --> 21:27.343
When I came here,

21:27.661 --> 21:33.512
It was very difficult to know what to buy, because you could look at a dealer's catalog and buy anything.

21:34.574 --> 21:41.087
And we couldn't do that, you know, responsibly, just in terms of buying.

21:44.734 --> 21:47.639
So, if you want to get a little insight, it's perfect.

21:47.659 --> 21:48.100
Yeah, exactly.

21:50.341 --> 22:02.151
There are many, many book dealers in town.

22:02.191 --> 22:04.834
We used book dealers.

22:04.994 --> 22:20.247
The way that we were able to build a collection was to use very good book dealers, rely on their expertise, let them know what we were looking for, and they were guaranteed.

22:26.183 --> 22:43.200
because we were paying, not outrageous prices, but we were on the high end of the market, because we were bringing in these large collections, things like Theodore Besterman's Duplicates.

22:43.361 --> 22:46.464
He gave his collection of old art books.

22:46.484 --> 22:52.630
It was published in this large catalogue to, it's actually right up there, it's dark blue and on the top shelf,

22:53.200 --> 22:55.463
And that seemed like an excellent collection.

22:55.503 --> 23:05.118
It was art historical, architectural, gardens, treatises, a great collection of a basic rare book library on art history.

23:06.079 --> 23:12.689
And that came through a dealer, and he had collated the books for us and guaranteed their quality.

23:13.129 --> 23:18.297
And so it's funny because at the time it seemed as though there were prices.

23:19.357 --> 23:21.199
They seem like the biggest bargains in the world.

23:21.259 --> 23:23.241
I was just thinking about that last night.

23:24.382 --> 23:28.426
Yeah, yeah.

23:28.507 --> 23:30.989
It's the big blue book on the top shelf.

23:31.009 --> 23:33.912
See the thing that says old art books?

23:33.932 --> 23:35.013
Just keep going to the right.

23:36.054 --> 23:37.316
To the right, to the right, to the right.

23:37.896 --> 23:38.177
There.

23:38.517 --> 23:39.878
Right there.

23:39.898 --> 23:42.761
We can take it out if you want to.

23:42.781 --> 23:43.382
Just pull it out.

23:43.923 --> 23:45.364
Oh, we can look at it later.

23:45.698 --> 23:50.327
One thing you'll notice is, notice that all the shelves in this library have these bars across the earthquake.

23:50.347 --> 23:54.354
And we've been having a lot lately.

23:54.574 --> 23:55.256
Earthquake bars.

23:55.997 --> 24:04.753
Because in the 94 earthquake, we realized that if people had been there, they would have, you know this famous picture of the book Fool?

24:05.088 --> 24:08.232
And, you know, the shelves are falling down on him, and he's dying.

24:08.252 --> 24:11.817
I don't know if that picture of it sounds pretty good.

24:11.977 --> 24:17.684
It's in the famous books of fools, and there's the book fool, and the shelf is about to destroy him.

24:17.704 --> 24:27.757
And since that was our experience during this last very severe earthquake, they did things like stabilize the shelves and then put fronts on them.

24:28.538 --> 24:31.622
And then down in our vaults, all the shelves are locked together.

24:31.662 --> 24:32.884
They're rolling, and they're locked.

24:33.353 --> 24:35.015
so that the books won't fall off.

24:35.076 --> 24:39.542
They're just big blocks of shelving on these rolling tracks.

24:40.023 --> 24:44.249
I thought they were places to hang them.

24:44.590 --> 24:45.050
No.

24:47.194 --> 24:48.335
Safety concerns.

24:48.415 --> 24:57.509
So basically you're developing two parallel collections of reference research type library and a rare book.

24:57.529 --> 25:01.535
And there are different policies for each one of those.

25:01.695 --> 25:03.057
The general library

25:03.863 --> 25:08.788
is now going towards being a library that documents world art.

25:08.848 --> 25:17.818
We started with traditional art history, so it was about Western European antiquity to contemporary.

25:18.579 --> 25:21.082
And then we brought in South America.

25:21.122 --> 25:22.664
We bought Australian collections.

25:22.684 --> 25:26.868
We didn't go too much into Africa and Asia because of the vernacular languages.

25:27.389 --> 25:32.014
We're now just about to discuss where we're going in terms of Asia.

25:32.467 --> 25:35.310
because so much more work has been done in art history in Asia.

25:35.751 --> 25:36.672
It's huge.

25:36.692 --> 25:36.912
Yeah.

25:37.793 --> 25:38.695
We worked like crazy.

25:38.715 --> 25:40.056
You can't imagine.

25:40.076 --> 25:45.523
I came from a state university library, the University of Missouri, which was an old art historical collection.

25:45.983 --> 25:47.946
They bought their books in the 19th century.

25:48.907 --> 25:49.808
Nice library.

25:49.828 --> 25:55.075
The College Art Association was founded in Missouri, so it was a very traditional, humanistic collection.

25:55.675 --> 26:00.381
My professor there, because I was the art librarian there and my degrees are from there,

26:00.952 --> 26:03.436
He was named Helmut Lehmannhaupt for years.

26:03.736 --> 26:04.978
He wrote the Krauss catalog.

26:05.699 --> 26:09.064
I met him, and I knew exactly what I wanted to do.

26:09.084 --> 26:10.105
I loved what he did.

26:10.726 --> 26:12.409
The art, you know, the art history and the book.

26:12.429 --> 26:14.692
Yeah, well, would you describe him as a mentor in this?

26:14.712 --> 26:17.977
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, a mentor and a kind of model.

26:18.117 --> 26:29.133
And he was very German, and so he came and he lectured, and he didn't chair and have office hours with students and things like that.

26:29.373 --> 26:30.435
He was very formal.

26:30.652 --> 26:52.174
But he was also a very interesting art historian who worked with early printing and some of the transitional books like the block books and the, what do you call it, the penning drawings in books and that kind of illustration.

26:52.194 --> 26:54.997
He did this famous book called Gutenberg and the Master of the Playing Cards.

26:55.897 --> 27:00.422
And he was amazing.

27:01.094 --> 27:02.696
wanted to do what he did.

27:02.756 --> 27:04.198
That was based on a shitey vibe on it.

27:04.538 --> 27:05.819
Yes, yes, exactly.

27:05.859 --> 27:13.308
The little bears and the, you know, things like that in the margins that they realized had actually been made from copper plates, from playing cards.

27:13.328 --> 27:15.390
Yeah, that's a very important monograph.

27:15.410 --> 27:16.171
Yeah, yeah.

27:16.191 --> 27:30.207
And then, here for me to be his research assistant, and I was so happy working for him for three years, and in that time we surveyed the Missouri stacks and we pulled the rare books out and put them in special collections, and it was an excellent experience for him.

27:30.338 --> 27:32.300
Were you planning to be a librarian at this point?

27:32.320 --> 27:35.444
I was just going to be an art librarian and work on rare books for my research.

27:36.085 --> 27:46.157
And then, I guess I was at Missouri for about ten years as the art librarian, and I taught courses in the literature of the humanities.

27:46.177 --> 27:55.327
So I talked about why music books looked different from Bibles, and when collected works started in the eighteenth century and nineteenth century.

27:55.347 --> 27:58.371
It was fun, because I could pull out rare books and show people.

27:58.891 --> 28:01.774
What do you mean by when collected books started?

28:02.154 --> 28:08.640
When collected books, when it was thought important to collect an author's work and do a kind of octavo edition of them.

28:08.660 --> 28:11.262
You don't think it was prior to that?

28:11.643 --> 28:12.143
Not too much.

28:12.203 --> 28:15.086
Pretty much the 18th century thing.

28:15.566 --> 28:17.067
Why theater books look different.

28:17.087 --> 28:21.972
How they evolved from playbooks to illustrated editions.

28:21.992 --> 28:22.993
It was really fun.

28:23.033 --> 28:24.414
I had a great time doing that.

28:24.434 --> 28:27.717
I had a wonderful old humanities collection.

28:28.372 --> 28:31.856
And I was able to come to UCLA and teach that for a while.

28:32.037 --> 28:42.350
And then, probably interesting enough for this book that you're writing, I realized when electronic and digitized things began to happen, that the course would have to change a lot.

28:43.071 --> 28:45.454
And I would have to do a lot more research.

28:45.474 --> 28:49.118
And we were beginning to move the collections and be open at that time.

28:49.219 --> 28:50.901
And I just went, you know what?

28:51.161 --> 28:55.847
I can't do this anymore because the book world is beginning to change.

28:56.333 --> 29:01.319
And the other thing was I didn't know how it was happening, and I felt kind of like the water was getting too deep.

29:02.080 --> 29:02.881
I got scared.

29:03.001 --> 29:05.364
I just thought, oh, I can't teach this course for a while.

29:06.105 --> 29:07.327
We don't have any perspective right now.

29:07.347 --> 29:08.208
What was the name of the course again?

29:08.228 --> 29:10.511
It was just called Literature of Humanities.

29:10.531 --> 29:14.336
But it went from the Renaissance to the 20th century.

29:14.356 --> 29:16.799
So what were you afraid about in terms of the computer, though?

29:16.819 --> 29:17.660
I didn't know what I was doing.

29:18.120 --> 29:21.885
You know, I needed to know all the different ways in which all the different humanities

29:22.169 --> 29:33.060
were adopting electronic formats or using those kinds of things and I would have had to go into philosophy and religion and I just kind of ran away.

29:33.460 --> 29:37.244
Is that impacting your thoughts on how you're collecting for the Getty now?

29:37.424 --> 29:39.427
Yes, very much so.

29:39.447 --> 29:50.758
What are the more permanent formats and what are the transitional ones and how is it important to try to collect some of those transitional formats, particularly in terms of special collections and

29:51.110 --> 29:57.778
in art history because the contemporary art world goes across media now.

29:58.559 --> 30:01.502
You know, they use videos and they use sound.

30:02.704 --> 30:06.629
They do performance art, artist books.

30:06.649 --> 30:09.532
So you're thinking maybe you don't need the printed books?

30:09.692 --> 30:10.073
Oh, no.

30:10.794 --> 30:11.695
Oh, no.

30:11.715 --> 30:13.337
Oh, no.

30:14.198 --> 30:16.340
I would jump off the balcony before I would say that.

30:16.400 --> 30:16.641
Oh, no.

30:16.681 --> 30:20.425
I think printed books, interestingly enough,

30:20.962 --> 30:25.247
are the format that has lasted the longest and is the most stable.

30:26.028 --> 30:28.170
Is that not interesting?

30:28.210 --> 30:29.131
That fascinates me.

30:29.171 --> 30:30.172
You're preaching to the choir.

30:30.292 --> 30:30.853
Yeah, I know.

30:31.073 --> 30:37.300
But that's like this kind of article of the first principle of my life.

30:37.540 --> 30:45.349
I like people who are eponymous, and so I like the fact that my name is Marsha Reed, and I love to read.

30:45.869 --> 30:54.760
And so I love to meet people who are like that, you know, who have names that say something about what their interests are.

30:54.800 --> 31:01.128
There's a dealer that I was just working with in New York last week, this man named Armin Kuntz, who works for C.J.

31:01.148 --> 31:03.631
Berner and Artemis Buxian.

31:03.651 --> 31:06.395
It's close enough to Kuntz so that, you know, he works in art.

31:07.136 --> 31:07.897
I like that.

31:08.357 --> 31:10.320
It doesn't always work.

31:11.061 --> 31:14.425
But you were saying how it is affecting your acquisition.

31:14.776 --> 31:16.618
Yeah.

31:17.159 --> 31:18.200
We have to stay with that.

31:18.280 --> 31:27.890
If we're documenting the literature, continue broadly, as how researchers work, we must take that into account.

31:28.751 --> 31:30.432
Otherwise, we would be in the lead-up category.

31:30.452 --> 31:35.478
Well, that question you have to take into account when you don't pursue one at the expense of the other.

31:36.639 --> 31:38.301
No.

31:38.321 --> 31:39.021
No.

31:39.061 --> 31:42.865
We would never be able to... If a monograph is published, you're going to acquire that monograph.

31:42.886 --> 31:43.006
Yeah.

31:43.026 --> 31:44.327
You're not going to wait and see it.

31:45.185 --> 31:56.704
But then all these, I mean, artists now are working very seriously on electronic formats, and we're discussing how are we going to collect that.

31:56.964 --> 31:58.807
Who is going to collect it?

31:58.827 --> 32:03.114
The other thing that's very clear, I think, is that you can't collect everything anymore.

32:03.195 --> 32:10.146
No library, no repository can do it all, and so you have to

32:11.645 --> 32:21.536
Have, at least in the corner of your eye, what other people are doing, and then that should inform your collecting in some way.

32:21.556 --> 32:29.185
Now, Marcia, you said you came in 1983, and I'm to remind you that we hope you have a copy of an essay that you wrote on.

32:29.205 --> 32:30.887
Yeah, the collector's books.

32:31.007 --> 32:35.052
Yeah, I'll write myself a note.

32:36.273 --> 32:39.357
But when you think about it, your tenure here,

32:39.843 --> 32:44.591
almost precisely coincides with this whole Internet explosion, doesn't it?

32:44.611 --> 32:45.492
Yeah, yeah.

32:45.512 --> 32:52.043
The 80s is when this thing, when the impact of it, when the consequences of it, when people start really saying the book is dead.

32:52.363 --> 32:52.644
Yeah.

32:52.764 --> 32:53.265
This is it.

32:53.325 --> 32:54.627
This is when it starts.

32:54.647 --> 33:01.057
About the time that she's coming here and is mandated to build and really given the... A library.

33:01.598 --> 33:05.985
Yeah, to build a library and to be given the... I mean, you must be the envy of everything.

33:06.522 --> 33:19.157
Well, except for the amount of work I have to do, they might want to, because everybody always says, even in New York, they call their club, oh, you guys have all the money, I guess you can buy anything.

33:20.238 --> 33:21.119
Terrible.

33:21.900 --> 33:28.327
That and the other statement that almost made me fall off my chair at dinner was, do you ever pay attention to the market value?

33:28.348 --> 33:31.391
Do you ever look at the, you know, just price of things you buy?

33:31.451 --> 33:33.053
Oh, yeah.

33:33.353 --> 33:35.055
That's all the work we do.

33:35.095 --> 33:42.264
We spend our life in the CD-ROM of American Book Price is Current, and then we do press research all the time.

33:43.105 --> 33:46.509
How anyone could think that we just cut a check?

33:46.709 --> 33:53.437
That's scary.

33:58.063 --> 34:01.487
Did you work on the Devices of Wonder exhibition now?

34:02.041 --> 34:05.946
Only because my colleague, we've been here the longest.

34:06.006 --> 34:10.672
Frances Turfak and I have both been here since 1983.

34:10.832 --> 34:17.521
And so as I was buying books, we were working very closely on things that she might be interested in.

34:18.001 --> 34:20.625
She says she's worked on that show for seven years.

34:21.286 --> 34:24.570
In fact, I think she's been thinking about it longer.

34:25.191 --> 34:31.879
The real genesis is that Werner Nikis collection of optical devices in pre-cinematics.

34:32.433 --> 34:41.647
books, but we're very close friends, and so in a way, peripherally, the department has seven curators, and it's very collaborative.

34:42.529 --> 34:49.279
So whenever it's a large collection that we're working on, it's usually a group of two or so, and then we discuss everything.

34:49.680 --> 34:53.686
But I do like the fact that you do pull from all the different departments, and you really do.

34:53.706 --> 34:55.128
It's a unique kind of an exhibition.

34:55.329 --> 34:59.976
Yeah, it's amazing.

35:00.378 --> 35:06.406
Everything does seem to generate from a collection that's here.

35:06.507 --> 35:13.877
Or group, you know, maybe... A group of things, I guess, but making sense, making a narrative out of the objects, perhaps, is that not fair?

35:14.257 --> 35:26.775
When I did this other show, which is called The Edible Monument, it was based on a special impression.

35:26.795 --> 35:27.516
The Edible Monument.

35:28.441 --> 35:33.809
Based on the festival collections, it had to do with banquets and presentation of food.

35:33.829 --> 35:45.808
And so sometimes it takes a thematic and then uses that thematic to tell people about things.

35:46.514 --> 35:51.222
I'm trying to find the recipe part.

35:51.422 --> 36:00.497
And it was really fun to do that, but I also, I'm always thinking that I want to tell people about a certain kind of rare book or collection.

36:01.018 --> 36:03.863
Yeah, you know what, and here's your folder.

36:03.963 --> 36:04.484
Here we go.

36:04.504 --> 36:08.891
These are the object lists for all of the grand toy shows.

36:09.011 --> 36:12.437
Oh, the press release.

36:12.603 --> 36:14.926
How about your current food marches?

36:15.046 --> 36:16.649
Yes.

36:17.550 --> 36:24.419
Because Edible Monument, I didn't realize that there's a huge world of foodies and gourmet cooks.

36:24.760 --> 36:26.742
Can we staple it right here so we don't have it?

36:26.762 --> 36:28.284
Sure, sure.

36:29.466 --> 36:31.970
You don't mind that we are.

36:31.990 --> 36:32.751
We won't get lost.

36:32.811 --> 36:35.594
We've seen a coordinator yet.

36:35.615 --> 36:39.640
A lot of papers and whatever.

36:39.974 --> 36:43.517
Oh, it was wild.

36:47.521 --> 36:50.483
You can't imagine what was going on.

36:50.503 --> 37:04.295
At one point, Martha Stewart wanted to come, and we got all kinds of publicity in the restaurant, and Bon Appetit, and Gourmet, and things like that.

37:04.936 --> 37:08.479
When was it?

37:08.712 --> 37:25.647
And what my big acts that I'm always trying to grind in a kind of, you know, not terribly, I don't know, heavy-handed way, was that this is why we collect our books.

37:25.667 --> 37:27.129
This is what you can find out.

37:27.169 --> 37:30.031
This is how you can know about what people did.

37:30.092 --> 37:35.176
I'm just making sure that when I hear really good things like that, I'm just making sure I'm getting it, which we are.

37:35.256 --> 37:36.137
Yep, go ahead.

37:36.944 --> 37:41.451
So it was so good, because of course the chefs didn't know about this.

37:41.471 --> 37:42.613
Of course the bread makers.

37:42.693 --> 37:48.903
We had people coming here to do demonstrations of how you actually made those things and with pictures.

37:48.963 --> 37:55.033
But then all the chefs arrived with their scrapbooks, and people were sending me videos of their food pieces.

37:55.113 --> 37:56.715
And it was wild.

37:56.996 --> 38:00.221
I didn't know that there was this enormous world of food.

38:00.241 --> 38:04.808
So not only the rare book people and the print people were interested in that, because that's what

38:05.075 --> 38:06.997
I thought the show was about.

38:07.638 --> 38:14.286
And festivals, ephemeral art made for festivals as shown in these books, because the courts would send them out.

38:14.947 --> 38:18.312
And then the other courts would copy and say, oh, look what happened to Versailles.

38:18.772 --> 38:20.414
We in Austria have to do this.

38:20.434 --> 38:23.318
So then they'd do a similar thing in Vienna.

38:23.338 --> 38:26.442
And they'd copy the Medici and stuff like that.

38:26.482 --> 38:28.144
So it was very interesting.

38:28.945 --> 38:30.567
But they have all these different dimensions.

38:30.647 --> 38:33.951
So whenever you put out your books on a certain subject,

38:34.420 --> 38:37.463
You get the print people and the book people and the science.

38:37.563 --> 38:45.652
The Fringe has huge amounts of people in science who are interested in the optical devices and the kinds of images that they take.

38:46.133 --> 38:48.576
But then we had a whole other section of the magicians.

38:50.498 --> 38:52.760
And then children like that show.

38:52.860 --> 38:56.545
Devices of Wonder was amazingly popular with children.

38:56.605 --> 39:00.529
So people came and then they made a second visit and they brought their children with you.

39:00.897 --> 39:13.013
Yeah, it's very nice to do things like that that aren't just for a certain public who could only appreciate old master drawings or paintings or things like that.

39:13.573 --> 39:15.956
People really like books.

39:16.777 --> 39:18.259
We really have to distinguish.

39:18.319 --> 39:25.369
I mean, Getty has what, seven different, or how many different characters?

39:25.389 --> 39:28.052
I guess what Tom does is really different from what you do.

39:28.285 --> 39:33.472
We've had books in a very generic sense, but maybe you could just tell us a little bit.

39:33.593 --> 39:37.959
What Tom does is study illuminated manuscripts, and that's a branch of art history.

39:38.400 --> 39:56.706
And what we do is talk about art history in terms of its documents, but not so much the high art that everybody associates with art history, like the Mona Lisa or like the well-known paintings, say,

39:57.445 --> 40:00.147
paintings of Rembrandt or something like that.

40:01.168 --> 40:09.956
Ours are not so valuable documents that art historians use or other people use.

40:09.976 --> 40:22.647
I mean, that's the other thing we're finding is that cultural historians come here and musicologists and theater historians to study visual aspects of it or to study descriptions.

40:23.328 --> 40:26.170
So this place is about

40:26.572 --> 40:34.242
research and study and scholarship, whereas the museum is really about exhibition of art itself.

40:34.262 --> 40:39.288
Two entirely different mandates, really, when you think about it in the same place.

40:39.309 --> 40:39.529
Yeah, yeah.

40:39.549 --> 40:42.593
I think it's interesting to talk about how the public enjoys the book or loves the book.

40:43.033 --> 40:50.503
Yeah, I mean, that's the interesting thing to me, is that people really like books, and they come into these exhibits

40:51.023 --> 40:55.329
And they start talking about their memories or their experiences.

40:55.449 --> 40:57.392
And maybe they do that with art.

40:58.073 --> 41:01.318
But I think books are more accessible to people.

41:01.378 --> 41:10.151
Or these objects like road maps or peep shows, they're a little bit more immediate in people's experience.

41:10.171 --> 41:15.819
Maybe they don't have a large painting on their wall of a mythological scene.

41:15.839 --> 41:17.001
But everybody reads books.

41:17.061 --> 41:18.984
Everybody owns books.

41:19.004 --> 41:20.406
Lots of people collect.

41:21.382 --> 41:22.243
That's the idea.

41:22.263 --> 41:27.312
People are really—collecting seems to be this activity, yeah.

41:27.793 --> 41:28.734
I guess that's what the N.T.

41:28.754 --> 41:29.736
Swoet Show tells us.

41:40.474 --> 41:47.305
Well, I love—they had an episode on—they've had their two brothers last week, you know.

41:47.504 --> 41:48.846
And it was for children.

41:49.327 --> 41:51.710
It was about getting children together, collecting.

41:52.131 --> 41:56.857
They have different episodes of the Antiques Roadshow in New Hampshire than I see here.

41:56.897 --> 42:00.062
It must be different public, you know, TVs.

42:00.082 --> 42:02.005
Yeah, I don't think they all had them at the same time.

42:02.786 --> 42:08.394
And the brothers had kept a notebook since I think they were, it was either age 8 or 11.

42:08.915 --> 42:16.245
And at the beginning of it, they wrote, we are antique collectors in this cute, you know, sort of children's handwriting.

42:16.512 --> 42:20.938
And then they were going around writing notes on each piece.

42:21.038 --> 42:22.460
They would try to draw a picture.

42:22.500 --> 42:23.762
They would take measurements.

42:24.263 --> 42:27.347
And it was about how you become a professional dealer.

42:28.289 --> 42:35.098
My father retired when he was 50, and he went to New Hampshire and sold military antiques and barometers.

42:35.759 --> 42:40.766
He's the second barometer maker in New Hampshire, and I have one of his barometers.

42:41.407 --> 42:42.869
He made his own barometers.

42:43.570 --> 42:44.832
They're really great.

42:45.098 --> 42:49.624
I went around with them to auctions for years, and I helped them carry chests and things like that.

42:49.644 --> 42:51.887
Oh, so I think this is a genetic thing.

42:51.907 --> 42:52.928
Yeah.

42:52.948 --> 43:06.065
So when I came here, unlike some of my colleagues in my department who were art historians, that world of the cell room and the auction and collecting and dealing, how you price things, how you put a secret code.

43:06.085 --> 43:09.229
We don't put secret codes for prices on things, but I know what those are.

43:09.809 --> 43:14.295
And so that world was great for me to get into in terms of books.

43:14.984 --> 43:25.016
I had bought books before, but not on the scale we were buying, but here, and bidding at auctions was easy for me, because I had just trailed around with my father for years.

43:25.097 --> 43:25.877
I knew about that.

43:27.079 --> 43:32.165
And it was fun, you know, it was really fun.

43:32.185 --> 43:32.366
Oh, yeah.

43:32.386 --> 43:44.080
Well, at the time I was working with him, I was always wanting to leave, because he was always in the back of the sale room, you know, and I was wanting to get him out, you know, and he was always hanging around, talking to other people, you know.

43:44.448 --> 43:52.443
Of the 800,000 books, how many of those would you say are rare books, special collections?

43:52.463 --> 43:57.753
The rare book collection is over 40,000, but it goes from Renaissance.

43:57.914 --> 44:01.360
You know, there aren't many inclinables that are about art, so I think we have

44:02.015 --> 44:03.417
27 incunables.

44:03.837 --> 44:11.167
Someone always sachets it and says, well, I'm interested in seeing your incunables collection.

44:11.227 --> 44:16.054
We're not the Huntington Library.

44:16.655 --> 44:18.397
So that's not what we did.

44:18.477 --> 44:20.460
And it goes through artist books.

44:20.480 --> 44:25.046
So of that over 40,000, it's probably up to about 45,000.

44:25.106 --> 44:26.187
Temporary artist books?

44:26.207 --> 44:27.809
We have contemporary artist books as well.

44:27.829 --> 44:30.553
So you must be a very interesting place for these.

44:31.478 --> 44:44.774
Yeah, I'm careful to buy things that go with the collection, so we don't have great deep collections in the craft of artists' books, because other people collect those.

44:45.856 --> 44:49.380
We're always very aware of what UCLA is collecting, what's at USC.

44:50.461 --> 44:53.445
We could never compete with the Huntington Library.

44:53.465 --> 44:56.929
Mr. Huntington bought 200 libraries.

44:58.343 --> 44:59.925
That was an amazing time.

44:59.985 --> 45:02.809
And he did about a hundred years or so.

45:02.829 --> 45:04.231
Yeah, yeah.

45:04.772 --> 45:10.319
There were amazing things available when he and Pierpop Morgan and other people like that were buying libraries.

45:10.339 --> 45:12.542
We could never play that game.

45:12.562 --> 45:13.403
He built the entire library.

45:13.844 --> 45:14.104
Yeah.

45:15.246 --> 45:16.988
He collected collections, as you say.

45:17.088 --> 45:18.330
Yeah, yeah.

45:18.871 --> 45:21.635
We did that, but on a much smaller scale.

45:21.655 --> 45:24.218
You know, so we laid this basis for our collections.

45:24.659 --> 45:27.102
Some of the initial collections, not the Besterman collections,

45:27.470 --> 45:35.742
But we bought a collection on 18th century neoclassicism, because 18th century for art history is, this is when art history began.

45:36.363 --> 45:48.640
And it was the collection of Robert de Belder, one of these two brothers, his brother George, also collected botanical books, and there was a very famous sale of his.

45:49.421 --> 45:51.204
But this is Robert de Belder's collection.

45:51.644 --> 45:52.566
He had fragments.

45:52.646 --> 45:57.072
We didn't buy fragments, you know, and objets.

45:57.203 --> 45:59.508
He had regular books as well.

45:59.688 --> 46:02.735
So we had a library that added to our general collections.

46:02.755 --> 46:10.090
And sometimes we bought rare books along with a regular library and laid the basis for the collection.

46:10.110 --> 46:11.934
But pretty much they were discreet.

46:12.395 --> 46:13.899
So there was a rare book collection.

46:14.380 --> 46:17.406
The Muzio Architectural Library was mostly rare books.

46:17.892 --> 46:24.097
on the history of architecture, and Giovanni Muccio was an architect who used those books.

46:24.117 --> 46:28.501
So that was a way that we got a leg up and had a quick base of collections.

46:28.521 --> 46:32.004
But it was nothing like White de Huntington's did.

46:32.124 --> 46:33.766
I'm pretty respectful of that collection.

46:33.826 --> 46:35.627
Well, it's very different, but then you're different things.

46:35.807 --> 46:36.128
Yeah.

46:36.148 --> 46:38.029
You're embarking on a different program.

46:38.550 --> 46:46.937
He was also, he was a private collector, and so like Morgan and some of the other ones, or some of the other collections that based theirs on

46:47.170 --> 47:02.326
We were buying, we knew that we were going to be an open to the public institution that would support the museum, but we're also open to the world.

47:02.486 --> 47:03.467
From the beginning, too.

47:03.528 --> 47:04.669
Yes, we knew that.

47:08.152 --> 47:11.636
We bought at a breathtaking level.

47:11.836 --> 47:15.220
I have never been so busy as when I came here and worked.

47:15.537 --> 47:18.201
But who would not want to do this?

47:18.221 --> 47:28.116
It was an incredible privilege to have the money to build a superb we were buying for condition and completeness.

47:28.837 --> 47:35.767
We wanted good copies that had a kind of historical accuracy and so we valued original condition.

47:36.528 --> 47:38.271
And that was something people didn't understand because

47:38.707 --> 47:40.609
People would say, isn't that book kind of shabby?

47:40.629 --> 47:42.191
And I'd say, no, it's uncut.

47:42.211 --> 47:44.674
It's an original paper wrapper.

47:44.815 --> 47:47.378
No, no.

47:47.718 --> 47:55.688
We actually didn't want those sort of beautiful Morocco bindings from the 19th century with lovely pressed copies, because that taste has changed.

47:57.090 --> 47:57.290
True.

47:57.370 --> 48:00.574
Is your whole catalog in line?

48:00.935 --> 48:01.035
Yeah.

48:01.100 --> 48:04.204
So we can just go home and punch up and see what you have.

48:04.264 --> 48:08.570
Yeah, except for things that have just come in the door, you know, collections that were currently processing.

48:08.591 --> 48:17.884
And that was the other thing is we didn't have to convert a catalog to an electronic format.

48:18.645 --> 48:21.989
We had a small catalog, but it wasn't very substantial.

48:22.009 --> 48:24.413
You had to go through this big retrospective conversion.

48:25.654 --> 48:31.022
What we did was we funded, the Getty Trust funded,

48:31.694 --> 48:37.642
projects for UCLA, for New Public Library, Michigan.

48:38.023 --> 48:45.253
We had good art libraries, and then we could use those cataloging records to do that.

48:45.273 --> 48:53.644
Chris, in less than 20 years, material that encourages... Probably.

48:53.664 --> 48:56.047
Yeah, probably.

48:56.148 --> 48:57.249
Oh, yeah.

48:57.569 --> 49:00.874
Yeah, yeah.

49:01.698 --> 49:03.741
Yeah, yeah.

49:03.761 --> 49:10.072
The good stuff isn't around anymore, that's really true.

49:10.092 --> 49:10.212
Right.

49:10.232 --> 49:10.452
Yeah, yeah.

49:10.472 --> 49:13.678
The good stuff—and look at this—are you going over fear?

49:13.978 --> 49:14.339
Oh, yeah.

49:14.439 --> 49:15.901
Oh, you've got to go over fear.

49:15.941 --> 49:16.262
Oh, yeah.

49:16.402 --> 49:18.205
I'm heading right out, yeah.

49:20.547 --> 49:43.669
With the internet, does that change the interaction with the US?

49:44.459 --> 49:48.584
I don't use the internet except for pricing.

49:49.045 --> 49:50.387
That is amazing.

49:50.727 --> 49:51.388
And rarity.

49:52.049 --> 49:55.453
Because if you punch something in... Books aren't as rare as you thought.

49:55.473 --> 49:56.895
Yeah, it's really interesting.

49:58.578 --> 50:01.381
Because we mostly get everything on approval.

50:02.222 --> 50:11.074
Because I'm just a hound of condition and I've trained the other curators to be that way about books, to really look for that.

50:11.273 --> 50:16.621
It's hard to buy on the Internet in that way.

50:17.442 --> 50:34.967
But just the ability, just all those online catalogues, the Research Libraries Group, Arlen, OCLC, to be able to see how many copies of books are out there, you know, to get a kind of rough estimate.

50:35.007 --> 50:38.732
When they worked on the ISTC, the Incutable Short Title Catalogues,

50:39.151 --> 50:41.835
Well, I realized how many copies of Incunibulls were around.

50:41.995 --> 50:43.358
How many of Nuremberg?

50:43.378 --> 50:43.638
What is that?

50:43.678 --> 50:47.103
Yeah, it's the Incunibull short title catalog.

50:48.546 --> 50:50.188
And that's in Arlen now.

50:50.649 --> 50:54.315
But there are hundreds of copies of the Nuremberg article.

50:54.335 --> 50:56.057
What were they doing in Nuremberg?

50:56.077 --> 51:00.905
You know, putting out, you know, sort of preliminary.

51:00.945 --> 51:03.008
Can anyone go on to that IACC?

51:03.088 --> 51:06.694
Well, it's part of Arlen now, so you can just subscribe to Arlen and get in.

51:07.636 --> 51:08.117
Yes.

51:08.157 --> 51:10.619
Oh, I know you can, yeah.

51:10.739 --> 51:11.921
Yeah.

51:12.481 --> 51:16.406
I went up there to use their American Book Crisis comic, the CD.

51:16.426 --> 51:20.050
I did a little idea with Kathy Green from the book, too.

51:20.070 --> 51:21.452
She's fascinating.

51:21.472 --> 51:21.852
You know Kathy?

51:21.992 --> 51:24.114
Yes, yes, yes.

51:24.135 --> 51:27.458
She was out here as an advisor for The World From Here.

51:27.478 --> 51:29.020
You know, did you get copies?

51:29.881 --> 51:30.902
Of the devices of one?

51:30.922 --> 51:32.604
Yeah, we have more of those.

51:32.684 --> 51:34.386
And what about The World From Here?

51:34.535 --> 51:38.700
The catalog, the one that was at the Hammer that's closed?

51:38.720 --> 51:41.924
No, no, I'm going to buy one of those in the bookstore, actually.

51:42.004 --> 51:45.509
