I'm happy to give you that.

51:48.252 --> 51:49.334
We have a copy.

51:49.354 --> 51:50.255
I can make a present.

51:50.395 --> 51:51.476
Would you like that?

51:51.496 --> 51:57.243
If only I can reciprocate with a present to you, I'll have to give it to you, but I'll take it on that.

51:57.283 --> 52:02.550
No, we have one thing to give to people who are particularly invested in the world of books,

52:02.834 --> 52:04.616
We had 80 books in that show.

52:05.558 --> 52:09.463
And I wrote some of the captions along with Bruce Whiteman and things like that.

52:09.823 --> 52:13.608
So it's a great catalog about libraries in Los Angeles.

52:14.289 --> 52:15.190
Somewhere there's a box.

52:15.210 --> 52:17.433
I think it's out there because I couldn't take all the boxes.

52:18.795 --> 52:22.640
That's the exhibition we wanted to see when we were out here.

52:22.660 --> 52:27.607
It was a really nice thing and it was very west coast because we had a lot of Asian books in there.

52:28.187 --> 52:32.453
So we were trying to really slant it to the world of the film industry.

52:33.007 --> 52:42.380
to the settlement of Los Angeles, the kind of things, big movie posters that are collected by institutions here.

52:42.480 --> 52:43.361
That's very interesting.

52:43.481 --> 52:49.670
If you find, is there kind of like an expatriate library attitude type of thing that you see?

52:49.690 --> 52:56.199
I mean, is there other Asian libraries here that might be the people of some Asian libraries in Asia, you know?

52:56.379 --> 52:56.840
I don't know.

52:57.100 --> 52:59.443
We're just beginning, I'm just working on that.

52:59.483 --> 53:02.187
My next exhibition I'm going to do after this is on China.

53:02.538 --> 53:13.248
And we've collected these books that are just bridging Europe and China and that view things produced in China, things produced in the West about China, putting them together.

53:13.828 --> 53:15.050
We're just working on that.

53:15.090 --> 53:31.785
Though one of our curators, the bibliographer, the person who is in charge of the general collections, just produced a position paper working with the UCLA, the Richard Rudolph Library, which is a very estimable Chinese-Japanese collection.

53:32.440 --> 53:35.905
And we're working on where we're going to go in terms of that.

53:35.925 --> 53:41.754
But there are very strong Asian collections, and so there were wonderful things in the world from here on.

53:43.076 --> 53:47.723
Chinese books, they have an amazing tradition that's much longer than ours.

53:47.983 --> 53:50.667
The first printed book is, what, the Diamond Sousa or something?

53:50.687 --> 53:51.629
Yes, yes.

53:51.709 --> 53:53.391
400 years, it speaks Gutenberg.

53:53.412 --> 53:55.855
Not with metal, but never the last printed book.

53:55.875 --> 53:57.117
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

53:57.137 --> 54:01.063
But you can use lots of different techniques to produce lots of different formats.

54:01.837 --> 54:14.529
And we're changing our formats right now for book production, so I wouldn't want to—although I'm very interested in books and printing myself, I would never want to say that's the only format that's important.

54:15.570 --> 54:21.496
One of the chapters in this next book is in all the different surfaces that we've recorded at Five Sines.

54:21.516 --> 54:23.117
Can you tell me something about that?

54:23.137 --> 54:25.880
Can we kind of turn you off for a while and let you talk about that?

54:26.040 --> 54:27.261
I'm kind of interested in that.

54:27.802 --> 54:30.004
That particular subject?

54:31.621 --> 54:43.778
We've had this kind of acrimonious interchanges because the things haven't been well described.

54:44.680 --> 54:50.468
And I had wonderful experience last week as I went to Christie's in New York.

54:50.488 --> 54:58.079
I thought we were going to bid on one of these 18th century auction catalogs by famous French collectors.

54:58.099 --> 55:01.223
There were these people, Mariette, Crozat, Rémy.

55:01.608 --> 55:04.651
And they were principals in auctions.

55:04.771 --> 55:06.133
They sold their own collections.

55:06.233 --> 55:07.694
They bought other people's collections.

55:08.295 --> 55:16.363
And the auction catalogs from that time, it's sort of mid to end of the 18th, maybe 1720s on.

55:16.463 --> 55:20.327
And it really documents very interesting collecting practices.

55:20.728 --> 55:26.233
This was a print catalog, a catalog of Quazat's print collection.

55:26.253 --> 55:29.016
And it supposedly was illustrated

55:29.283 --> 55:42.743
by these little tiny vignettes that this artist, Gabriel de Saint-Aubin, had put in the margins and they showed the paintings and the drawings that were offered for sale in the catalogs.

55:42.763 --> 55:45.627
They were collector's objects since the 18th century.

55:46.128 --> 55:57.585
And this was purportedly a catalog of one of the collectors and auctioneers, Pierre Rémy, illustrated by Saint-Aubin.

55:57.920 --> 56:10.896
As you were reading this, we realized that they had been cut out and put in the Oakland catalogs, so we thought that's very interesting that it's not like the other catalogs, which are just, you know, have marginal vignettes on the page.

56:11.557 --> 56:17.584
And then as I worked on it, I realized this thing has been put together, and the things that were by St.

56:17.624 --> 56:21.409
O'Bend didn't correspond to the entries in the sales catalogs.

56:21.429 --> 56:27.336
In fact, we didn't know what they were, but they were taken from another catalog because they had little catch numbers on them.

56:27.940 --> 56:28.922
Yeah.

56:28.942 --> 56:38.378
And then, when they said that it had been annotated by Pierre Grenier, there was no evidence whatsoever in this catalog that they were buying him.

56:38.398 --> 56:42.906
They were hypothesizing because he wasn't mentioned as one of the buyers.

56:43.106 --> 56:44.609
Well, that doesn't mean anything.

56:44.629 --> 56:45.390
It's interesting.

56:45.410 --> 56:45.610
Yes.

56:46.492 --> 56:48.295
And then...

56:48.865 --> 56:51.929
And from that, we looked at the location.

56:52.069 --> 56:57.977
No, it was somebody new, and he was a very interesting guy.

56:58.118 --> 56:59.900
I don't want to get into it.

56:59.960 --> 57:03.325
Oh, I'm going to get into it.

57:03.385 --> 57:06.730
But he had described it in, you know, the best possible way.

57:06.850 --> 57:10.755
In fact, I think it was kind of put together in the 19th century.

57:11.393 --> 57:25.089
by a collector who wanted to mimic these catalogs that had been done in the 18th century, because the binding was 19th century, and the whole thing had a kind of 19th century look to it.

57:25.109 --> 57:26.851
This is one of the original catalogs.

57:26.871 --> 57:31.957
It's a bad draft copy, but this is what the catalogs really should have looked like.

57:32.718 --> 57:34.660
Even the writings look 19th century.

57:34.720 --> 57:39.105
We had the information in our copies of the sale catalogs that we have already.

57:39.372 --> 57:42.601
We had the buyer and we had the price, so we really had that information.

57:43.202 --> 57:48.116
There were a couple annotations that commented on the taste of a particular work.

57:48.777 --> 57:50.402
They weren't interesting.

57:50.422 --> 57:54.192
And so to go and look at this thing, which is what that is,

57:54.610 --> 58:00.417
And then we went the next day to these, they turned out with the Morgan, and we looked at the real things, and we looked at the quality of the drawings.

58:00.938 --> 58:05.763
Even the quality of the drawings, they were blurred, they were ripped in some cases.

58:05.784 --> 58:07.446
You couldn't really see it.

58:07.466 --> 58:12.251
This beautiful picture of Los Angeles that they showed is wisdom.

58:12.392 --> 58:18.158
In the catalog, it didn't even seem to be like they were at the center bed, so that was awful.

58:18.499 --> 58:20.381
I'm looking at your notes here, you really did.

58:20.401 --> 58:22.744
Oh, it was really fun, because I was working with a dealer,

58:23.011 --> 58:32.185
And then the next year we went to the Morgan and we realized, oh, wait a minute, these things in this catalog hardly look like it, plus the book is problematic.

58:32.205 --> 58:33.027
So we didn't bid on it.

58:33.347 --> 58:36.332
But I went to the auction, you know, how could I not go to the auction after that?

58:36.352 --> 58:37.694
I was growing up time anyway.

58:38.455 --> 58:46.989
And it's sold for $80,000 to the end.

58:47.449 --> 58:49.693
And maybe they knew something.

58:49.977 --> 58:52.741
I wouldn't touch this thing because I didn't know it.

58:52.821 --> 58:59.351
And then the dealer that I worked with, he just went and met me because he had seen it once and then we were meeting with Christine to really go through it.

58:59.731 --> 59:00.753
And it was fun to go through it.

59:00.853 --> 59:01.875
You know, he read the whole thing.

59:01.895 --> 59:04.318
So it was very, you know, very educational.

59:05.059 --> 59:08.324
And he said, he said, this thing has red flags all over it.

59:08.885 --> 59:11.669
And it did.

59:11.689 --> 59:11.749
So.

59:12.067 --> 59:15.892
And so it was so much fun.

59:15.932 --> 59:16.873
Who was the underbid?

59:16.933 --> 59:19.216
You know, the bidding was very spirited.

59:19.236 --> 59:21.719
I just stood at the back of the room and died.

59:21.840 --> 59:24.403
I just thought, have these people really looked at this thing?

59:24.423 --> 59:25.344
And this was 20 to 30.

59:25.364 --> 59:28.108
So it tripled the estimate.

59:28.128 --> 59:30.751
And we were prepared to go a certain way on it.

59:30.951 --> 59:33.515
So you might have brought it if the price was right.

59:33.535 --> 59:38.621
Well, if the thing was okay, though, but as soon as we looked at it, we looked at it.

59:38.681 --> 59:41.685
And what I thought was maybe everybody else would think that.

59:42.239 --> 59:45.303
And we would go back and maybe it would be bought in and we could get it.

59:45.763 --> 59:49.828
But because we didn't know what it was, and maybe there was something that VN knew.

59:49.888 --> 59:51.049
Maybe they knew what this was.

59:51.590 --> 59:55.434
But if I don't know what it is... I'm curious to find out.

59:55.454 --> 59:58.258
Oh my goodness, I'm buying her institution.

59:58.278 --> 01:00:00.060
You know, it's too scary.

01:00:00.080 --> 01:00:03.444
And the dealer agreed was that this was way too scary.

01:00:03.464 --> 01:00:10.812
But it was fascinating because it was some kind of object that someone had made to look like a center back catalog.

01:00:10.994 --> 01:00:12.856
But it was, oh, it was really fun.

01:00:12.876 --> 01:00:14.357
But I like auctions.

01:00:14.457 --> 01:00:22.325
I mean, I like these 18th century auctions, because this is sort of the, you know, the heart of when auction sales really get going.

